Food to Blame European Inflation
The main reason for the rise in inflation measured in the euro area is the rapid rise in food prices.
In the 13 euro-zone countries, inflation was higher than expected in November - an annual inflation rate of 3.1 per cent was recorded after the 2.6 per cent in October, as reported by the EU Statistical Office in Luxembourg.
Official forecasts are based on only 3%, Bloomberg reported.
Unlike the US, UK, and Canadian central banks, the European Central Bank (ECB) has not lowered the Leitzsin. At its discretion, the cut in interest rates would favour rising commodity prices and the slight fall in unemployment to create an inflation spiral.
The ECB strives to keep inflation below two percent, or at least close to the two percent mark.
According to an analyst, the ECB is in a mess: inflation must be "agreed" in order to avoid the need for action later.
At 3.3 percent, the inflation rate reached a 12-year record high in Germany in November; in Spain, the rate rose from 3.6 to 4.1 percent.
The rise in inflation in the euro area is due to the rise in food and energy prices.
The MATIF wheat quotations rose by 88 percent, and the price of soybeans also reached a record high since 1973.
Food oil and dairy products also experienced a significant inflation in 2007.
The world price of crude oil rose by 52 percent this year - last month the price per barrel of black gold reached nearly 100 US dollars.
According to the ECB, inflation will rise from 2.1 to 2.5 percent in 2008, but is expected to decline to 1.9 percent in 2009.
For the next 3-4 months, analysts expect a 3-percent inflation rate, but estimate the annual average rate at 2.1 percent.
For 2008, experts expect the ECB to reduce interest rates twice.
Gallup orts government crisis
After long stagnation, the number of Fidesz sympathizers has grown considerably until the beginning of December. For the first time since 2002, the party has had the largest base camp, while the support for the Socialists has reached an unprecedented low of 13 percent, according to Gallup.
In the case of party-faithful voters, the difference is clear thanks to the high determination of the opposition advocates: more than two thirds (71 percent) are in favour of the MSZP for a fifth (20 percent).
According to the survey, MDF and SZDSZ are below the parliamentary threshold: they reach two percent of the total population.
The number of party voters has grown by one percent in both camps.
Compared to the last low point, the general economic sentiment has continued to deteriorate - never before has the proportion of those who consider the country's economic situation to be "pronouncedly bad" been so high (41 percent), while another 46 percent consider it "fairly bad".
After more hopeful prospects in spring and summer, families see the change in their financial situation again more pessimistic.
For the coming year, the majority of the population expects the situation to deteriorate further; only a tenth expect improvement.
A Gallup survey conducted in December showed that 71% of respondents - a historical high - considered the Prime Minister's work "rather bad than right".
Thirteen percent of respondents have great confidence or trust in Ferenc Gyurcsány in general, while the percentage of supporters for Viktor Orbán is 38 percent.
Around 54% do not trust the head of government at all, compared with 27% distrust of Fidesz party leader.
One of the indicators of political sentiment is the number of people who think that dissatisfaction with the Prime Minister could be managed even without a change of government.
If, after the unrest last October, 35% had still voted in favour of the government and the head of government, this share is now only 20%, while the relative majority (33 percent) sees the solution only in new elections.
Asked about their interest in the referendum, 60 percent replied that they would "certainly" participate, and another 20% would "probably" vote.
By way of comparison, if the parliamentary elections were to take place this Sunday, only 55 percent would go to the polls "with certainty", and another 15% would consider their participation "probably". In view of these trends, the result of the referendum would be foreseeable.
74% would vote against tuition fees, 79% against the practical fee, and 84% against the hospital daily allowance.
Transferred to the group of participants in the referendum "with certainty" the proportion of opponents of the study, practice and hospital fees would amount to 81, 84, and 89 percent respectively.
