In many places, disinfectants are saved
This year, more than a thousand infections were registered in hospitals due to improper use of antibiotics.
Sanitary conditions in hospitals, overcrowding of beds, overcrowding of staff - all factors that are not conducive to the containment of infections, according to the leading physician of the National Epidemiology Center.
In many places, disinfectants are also saved.
The traumatology department of János Hospital recently diagnosed MRSA infection.
The antibiotic-resistant bacterium was found in a male patient who was hospitalized after a serious accident.
The patient was isolated.
At the beginning of the year there was already a similar infection here.
The injured in a serious car accident was released from the hospital, but a little later the man had to return with an MRSA infection. An important operation could not be performed since then because of the bacterium, which is still in the patient's body.
Until 10 December of this year, multi-resistant pathogen-induced infections from hospitals were reported to the National Nosocomialis Surveillance System in 1094, according to the leading physician of the National Epidemiology Centre, Karolina Böröcz.
So many infections caused by multi-resistant pathogens were safely registered in hospitals, but the dark figure is likely to be higher.
Approximately two thirds of the infections (683 cases) were caused by MRSA, the staphylococcus aureus resistant to methicillin oxacillin.
The Staphylococcus aureus (SA) bacterium carries about a third of the people in its nose without causing a disease.
SA-related infections (such as throat inflammation, tonsillitis, inflammation of the skin or wounds) usually react well to antibiotics, they are well curable.
However, if the drugs are dosed too high or used improperly, the well-responding bacteria produce antibiotic-resistant bacteria, which spread rapidly in hospitals under appropriate conditions.
Especially in patients with weakened, or permanently poorly functioning immune system, but also in older, or patients with low body weight, these bacteria can cause serious infections, such as wound infection or blood poisoning, i.e. sepsis.
According to the medical director of János Hospital, the MRSA infection is nothing special, such incidents are part of the everyday illness.
The infection should not be confused with the epidemic, warned Tibor Nyulasi - MRSA there is only no where it is not wanted.
Resistant to antibiotics
"Such patients are isolated, the nurses wear rubber gloves and masks in the care, and we have the antibiotics necessary for the treatment" - says Tibor Nyulasi.
While the patients are being examined for MRSA when they are admitted to the hospital, an infection cannot always be avoided.
Sampling too rare
The majority of MRSA-induced infections in hospitals would be avoidable, but the current conditions and circumstances are unfavourable to the control of the formation or spread of the multi-resistant pathogen, says Karolina Böröcz.
After this infection occurs predominantly in hospitals and nursing homes, hospitals should examine the patients who have been admitted and isolate MRSA-infected immediately.
However, microbiological sampling is not so common in Hungarian hospitals.
Not least because there are no subsidies from the State sickness fund for this investigation.
Most cases would therefore only come to light when the patient already has a noticeable MRSA infection, according to the medical director of the epidemiology center.
There are strict recommendations from the European Union on the appropriate use of antibiotics in human medicine, but there are also guidelines for the treatment of certain infections and diseases in Hungary.
Antibiotic therapies should be targeted, i.e. microbiological tests are necessary to prevent resistance to the drug, but this directive is not always complied with by hospitals.
Among the outpatients or patients in basic care, microbiological sampling is even more rare, says Karolina Böröcz.
The disinfectants are saved
Scientific evidence shows that MRSA is most often transferred from one patient to another by the nursing staff.
This is precisely why washing your hands or wearing gloves and masks is of great importance, but there are also significant deficiencies in this area in hospitals.
MRSA is transmitted by droplet infection or contact, but there is not always the possibility to isolate the infected patient in the home hospitals.
The rooms are even often overcrowded, the beds are lined up in a row, although there should be a distance of at least 1.5 meters between them from an epidemiological point of view.
As Karolina Böröcz continues to note, unfortunately, in the financially less well-placed hospitals, it even happens that disinfectants are saved, there are few nurses, many patients - all factors that favour the emergence of infections.
Such infections are proven to be far less common there, or the further spread of the pathogen can be stopped where these protective measures are observed, says Karolina Böröcz.
Government programme against MRSA
Getting MRSA infections under control causes the health insurance companies enormous costs, so they are being fought everywhere.
In England, for example, the prevention of MRSA or its containment was recorded in the government programme.
After initial signs, the program is successful - as published data show, the trend of MRSA infections in England is declining.
The European Centre for Disease Prevention (ECDC) has identified the prevention of the emergence of multi-resistant pathogens (including MRSA) and the prevention of infections in hospitals as one of its priorities.
