A further EUR 400 million for infrastructure
Finance Minister János Veres and Marta Gajecka, Vice-President of European Investment Bank (EIB) signed three EUR 400 million credit agreements in Budapest on Friday. The money will go to education, transport and environmental infrastructure and the energy sector.
In 2006, the European Investment Bank (EIB) approved a EUR 300 million framework for the financing of transport and environmental projects implemented by the Cohesion Fund. The loan agreement of EUR 100 million was signed earlier and the current agreement concerns the use of the EUR 200 million lent.
The amount of EUR 150 million agreed in the loan agreement is also to be spent on the budget financing of educational projects.
The EIB has granted a total of EUR 300 million for this purpose for Hungary and the remaining EUR 150 million will be decided later as part of the extension of the loan agreement.
In the field of innovation, the contracting parties have signed an agreement of EUR 50 million, which will mainly be channelled into research and development programmes at the University of Debrecen.
At the meeting, the subway line 4 was also discussed.
It was agreed that as soon as Hungary has clarified the details of the underground financing with the EU, the original contract and any modifications will be discussed again.
According to János Veres, this would be possible in the first quarter of 2008.
Since 1990, the EIB has financed a total of 113 projects totalling EUR 8.4 billion in Hungary.
The loan interest is EURIBOR-linked, the loan is provided by the EIB with a delay of 8 years, without any commission.
Bulgaria, the real estate paradise of the EU
The development of the Bulgarian real estate market is fabulous - all of Europe looks attentively at the previously rarely mentioned Balkan state.
What, where, and who is still buying the cheapest market in the EU, but is rapidly becoming more expensive?
An analysis of the Bulgarian Re/Max Division.
Bulgaria is without a doubt the most sought after place for real estate purchases in Eastern Europe, with cheap ski apartments and houses by the sea.
Between the mountains the regions Bansko, Borovec, Pamprovo and Vitosa are among the most popular, by the sea are Albena, the "gold coast", the "sun coast", and the historic towns of Sozopol and Nessebar the racers, however, real estate around Kavarna and Balcik are also increasingly in demand.
According to Re/Max analysts in Bulgaria, the interior of the country will soon or later attract investors, such as Veliko Tarnovo, Gabrovo, Elena, and Triavna, as well as the very favorable area of Ruse, with more buyers.
The capital Sofia also offers tempting offers - commercial and office areas offer highest returns.
Bulgaria is well on its way to becoming one of the most attractive European golfer's paradises, attracting tourists in addition to the summer and winter seasons in the other two seasons.
Prospective investors are therefore already buying in on a large scale, for example around Bansko.
According to analysts, people who buy real estate in Bulgaria also strive for a change in their lifestyle.
Most buyers are English, but there are also interested parties from France, Belgium, Spain, and more and more from Romania.
Investors from Malta and Cyprus are also present, while there are mainly Russian buyers in the Black Sea and ski resorts.
There are three groups of foreign buyers, says Georgij Jankov, Regional Director of Re/Max Bulgaria.
Those who want to settle down buy either revitalized real estate by 50-100,000 euros, or run-down houses by 5-15,000 euros, which they then renovate themselves.
Good connections and accessibility as well as communication possibilities are important, but also the proximity to a big city, shops and doctors are crucial for the buyers.
The second category includes those who are looking for a holiday home (Bulgaria was listed among the top ten holiday destinations of the Germans in December).
The third group consists of businessmen who invest with the aim of a medium to long-term increase in value.
However, real estate in the capital is constantly becoming more expensive, due to the ever-growing demand.
Within the EU, real estate prices are the lowest in Bulgaria, but there has been an annual price increase of 21 percent over the past five years.
The price of real estate prices far exceeds the rise in salaries.
Fodor and the six Hungarian percent
As Environment Minister Gábor Fodor announced, the expert meetings will end on Tuesday, and the debate on the international climate regime after 2012 will continue by ministers on Wednesday after the official opening.
Experts and politicians from 192 countries are discussing the Bali Roadmap, which sets out the post-2012 emission-reducing measures, i.e. after the end of the Kyoto Protocol.
There is currently a heated debate between developed and developing countries.
The US has already signaled that they do not want to negotiate concrete figures, but they would be willing to reduce greenhouse gas emissions by 25-40 percent by 2020 compared to 1990.
The other major question at the conference is whether the industrialised countries are prepared to support developing countries both financially and technologically, in addition to reducing emissions.
An agreement has also been reached on support for developing countries.
The adjustment fund under the Kyoto Protocol is to be managed by a 16-member council, probably by the UN's Global Environment Facility (GEF), as can be seen in the "Piac és Profit".
Hungary's six percent
Environment Minister Gábor Fodor, on behalf of Hungary, supports the EU's desire to maintain its leadership in global climate action and to reach a new international agreement by 2009.
The Minister said that the EU would reduce greenhouse gas emissions by 20% by 2020 (as measured by 1990 levels), regardless of whether or not the "Agreement after 2012" was achieved successfully. The Union would even be willing to support a 30% reduction if other major industrialised countries in the world, or developing countries, are also willing to fulfil their commitments in a strong and responsible manner.
Gábor Fodor stressed that the objective of the countries that had acceded to the Kyoto Protocol in 1997 was a reduction of only 5.2 percent, whereas the EU, with its then 15 member states, had already committed itself to a reduction of 8%.
The target for Hungary is a 6% reduction in greenhouse gas emissions compared to 1985-87 - a target that the country will definitely meet, as can be seen in the Ministry of Environment's press release.
The deployment is high in Bali - after all, the long-term international climate agreement has to be completed within two years, otherwise it would certainly not enter into force until after 2012. In this case, the reduction plans set out in the Kyoto Protocol would not follow a new international emission reduction system, the importance of which was also highlighted by the IPCC, the UN's Nobel Peace Prize-winning scientific climate change committee in its latest report.
This would delay emission reduction and increase the Earth's average temperature by more than 2°C would be unavoidable, which, according to scientists, would result in extremely serious and irreparable consequences.
British Army advertises on YouTube
British Army units have published footage of operations in Iraq and Afghanistan to increase popularity on the video portal.
First of all, the British Air Force (RAF) has discovered YouTube for itself: Special Forces stationed in Afghanistan have been launching videos of operations against the Taliban since March 2006, reports the BBC.
The images shot with helmet mounted miniature cameras are controlled at the air force base in Kandahar and then sent to London, where they are placed on the Internet.
Political message inevitable
Soldiers of the Luftwaffe have already contributed 139 such images, their "channel" was viewed more than 75,000 times.
The British Ministry of Defence was registered under "defenceheadquarters" in the spring of 2007 to publish videos about Iraqi and Afghan operations, but also the British Ministry of Foreign Affairs (Commonwealth Office) and the Iraq-based international peacekeepers (MNFI) have their own YouTube channels.
Operation in Afghanistan
Originally, the Luftwaffe has published the videos with the aim of recruiting soldiers, and as the Ministry of Defense says, the contributions also serve the purpose of informing the population about the actual goals of foreign missions.
According to defense expert Gordon Mackenzie of the BBC, such published propaganda is almost free of charge compared to traditional television advertising, but these videos always carry a certain amount of political message, as they confirm the existence of the military measures decided by the government in their own way.
Americans advertise with game
However, the army must also fight against amateur recordings, which, in addition to carefully edited, censored recordings, also make it online - such as those that show the death of the soldiers: in the somewhat hypocritical, "official" propaganda films, at most, the losses are talked about, but the bloody sides of the war are not shown.
By the way, many of the war scenes in Iraq and Afghanistan have already been uploaded to the platform, but the British have only recently discovered this "gating".
The Americans, however, advertise in a slightly different way, namely with the free downloadable shooting game "America's Army", in which the player can slip into the skin of the soldier as part of a more or less life-scattered simulation.
