The fourth point is that the VDSZZZ, which belongs to the League of Trade Unions, did not accept the offer submitted by the Ministry of Transport concerning the sidelines and now calls for a new concept.
Political Capital: Hungarian Guard Increases State Risk
According to the Risk Analysis Division of Political Capital, the activities of the Hungarian Guard, which was founded this August with the support of the "Movement for a Better Hungary", have increased the risk of Hungary and the region in several ways.
The Institute's "Risk Warning Report" states, among other things: In connection with the activities of the Hungarian Guard, the highest political risk is the "strengthening of the existing ethnic tensions between the Gypsies and non-Gypsies in Hungary, which could even lead to violent ethnic conflicts in the short term".
The main reason for this was the Hungarian Guard's strategy, which probably aims at provoking such an argument, according to the research institute.
As reported, this is seen as a failure on the part of the political leaders: "People of public life have left the discussion of the Roma question to representatives of radical political groups who have now built their political strategy on the Roma-Hungary contrast".
It is thought that this would exacerbate the problem, make reasonable dialogue impossible, favour extremities, and increase the likelihood of violent confrontations.
The research institute also believes that the activities of the Hungarian Guard, not least thanks to the enormous attention of the local and foreign media, "have seriously damaged the image of Hungary abroad, especially in terms of confidence in stability and democratic maturity".
We remember: Since autumn 2006 the reorganization of radical and extremely right-wing groups in Hungary has been constantly on the upswing, so that since summer 2007 several organizations called themselves "national self-defense association" have been founded.
"It is common for these groups to define themselves as civil organizations, while openly boasting that they are preparing their members for - sometimes armed - defence tasks (disaster protection, national defence, orderly protection), relying on the incompetence of the police, the army, or the state itself," it was said.
And further: all this is done according to the method that tries to disguise various political aspirations as bourgeois initiatives, based on the political and party-riddenness of the population.
The emphasis on the civil character and the form of the association does not merely serve to circumvent legal barriers that could arise in the course of registration with the court - it is also a political strategy.
As can be seen from the analysis, the activities of the Hungarian Guard are also a risk-enhancing factor for relations with neighbouring countries.
"In recent months, the Hungarian Guard has been cited as a potential source of danger in several neighbouring countries, some ultra-nationalist politicians in certain neighbouring countries see the emergence of the Hungarian Guard as confirming its own anti-Hungary policy.
All of this has an impact on the political stability of the region" - it was said.
From the point of view of the research institute, the establishment of the Hungarian Guard is not a single phenomenon in Central East Europe, so the political risk for the entire region has grown.
As reported, the activities of the Hungarian Guard are comparable to those of the Bulgarian National Guard, whose foundation was announced in August 2007 by the far-right Bulgarian National Union (BNU).
In the background of the creation of the Bulgarian Guard were the Roma mass riots that took place in a district of Sofia (Krasna Poljana).
The BNU took the incidents as an opportunity to establish the National Guard, arguing that the goal of the organisation was "national protection".
