Festive days are not everywhere holidays
In Hungary, holidays are regulated by law, so that the practice of redistributing the working days around the holidays has become established, but the coming year will bring us less such days.
In the EU and in America, too, something else is understood as "holiday".
The Hungarian legal system distinguishes between state holidays and work-free days.
Unemployed days are mostly church holidays, or are associated with important historical events.
For example, we also celebrate New Year's Day: both the last day of the old and the first day of the new year are work-free days - the latter alone so that the New Year's Eve celebrations can rest.
Throughout the year we have a total of fourteen holidays.
The state holidays are March 15, which commemorates the revolution of 1848, and October 23rd, the anniversary of the revolution of 1956.
On 20 August the foundation of the state, on 1 May the work is celebrated, on 1 and 2 November we commemorate our dead.
In addition, there are two holidays each at Easter, Pentecost, and Christmas.
Since our state, national or religious holidays rarely fall on a weekend, the practice of "working day postponement" has proven itself in cases where we would work only one day before or after the holiday.
The price of the extended weekends, however, is that we have to work very well on the Saturdays before, or go to school.
When this day, which falls before or after the holiday, is finally to be worked out, the Minister of Labour has for many years laid down a separate regulation.
The legislation applies equally to all employers and employees, public employees and civil servants.
Only companies and institutions in which the operation is continued without interruption, i.e. also on the holidays, are excluded.
This year, the work order is only a little confused by the holidays at the end of the year: from 24 December, life in this country will remain formal, since most of the days between Christmas and New Year's Eve will take time off, or the holiday that has been suspended for this purpose.
Next year, there will be more holidays in the middle of the week, or at the end of the week, so that there will be fewer redistributions in the working days than this year.
The calendar is first "turned upside down" around the day of work, so that people can stay at home for four days at a time.
Saturday, April 26th will be a working day so that Friday, May 2nd can be a rest day.
The second re-disposal is related to the holiday on October 23rd: On Saturday, October 18th, the Friday, October 24th will have to be completed in advance.
The end of the year, however, will stand completely in the sign of the holidays, after everything will lie down and stop from 24 December, even if New Year's Eve falls on a Wednesday.
