Winston Churchill, Ava Gardner, Frank Sinatra.
In Havana, skyscrapers grew, across the wide boulevards drove cars, which were among the cult symbols of the fifties of the last century.
Ernest Hemingway bought an estate in San Francisco de Paula, near Havana, and in Cojímar he had his yacht.
On the walls of the Bodeguita del Medio, stars of show business and politicians from all over America left their signatures.
And today?
You can leave your autograph on the walls of Havana's bodeguita.
At the bar at the Hotel Nacional you can mix cocktails as you wish.
And the cult cars of the fifties drive around in Havana until today, because the once imported Schigulis and Fiats have already fallen apart in the salty and humid air.
