Other places are being cleaned up, for example Trinidad.
In view of the fact that tourism brings much-needed money, there was a green light for this development.
Over the past fifteen years, new hotels have been built not only in Havana, but also in Varadero, along the coast of Holguín Province, and on islets such as Cayo Coco, Cayo Guillermo and others.
Cuba offers a moth that is unique in the world and attracts mainly railway lovers.
The sugar cane of remote plantations brought steam and diesel-powered narrow gauge railways to the sugar factories.
Their fleet has not been renewed for decades, and so you can see clean and fully functioning locomotives, whose peers have long been standing in the museum elsewhere.
Excursion destinations
Most of Cuba's visitors do not miss the most important places.
So you don't have to write in detail about Varadero or Havana anymore.
Just mention that there is a museum in Hemingway's already mentioned estate, whose visit should not be missed by the one who likes this writer.
The Viñales Valley in the west of the island is one of the most picturesque spots in Cuba.
The lush vegetation grows on lime soil.
The mogotas, limestone hills and rocks, rise steeply from the valley floor, in their cavities fertile soil accumulated, through which also weathered rock areas are covered by dense vegetation.
This valley is where perhaps the best Cuban tobacco is grown.
In its final form, you can meet him when you visit one of Havana's cigar factories.
It may also seem interesting to some people that the Chilean episode of the television series "Major Zeman" was filmed there.
Trinidad
An ancient city that was founded shortly after the Spaniards colonized the island.
The trade in slaves and sugar brought her fame and wealth.
The wealth was embodied in the beautiful beauty of the small town.
Spanish colonial architecture, strongly influenced by the later French settlers, has hardly changed for four hundred years.
Trinidad, located between the sea and the Escambray Mountains, is such a remote place that there was no road that would have connected the area to the rest of the country in the fifties of the last century.
This isolation helped to keep it unnoticed.
Nothing was built there, but therefore nothing was torn down, everyone was glad that he had a roof over his head.
If you have more than one afternoon for Trinidad, then it is worth visiting interesting places in the area, such as Playa Ancón Beach or the "Valley of Sugar Factory".
In the evening one should then go to the Casa de la Música, which revives after the darkness, and where the music does not remain silent until the morning.
Baracoa
This small town in the east of Cuba is considered by some to be the most beautiful of the island.
Certainly this view is also influenced by the way there.
Both roads, which lead from Guantánamo there, must overcome high and rugged mountains and run through a landscape that is hardly touched by human intervention.
UNESCO included this eastern outpost of Cuba in its World Heritage List, thanks to its untouched nature.
The best chocolate is produced there, the church shows the cross of Columbus (in fact it was created about a hundred years after Columbus' journeys), and the hill where the former castle, the current Hotel El Castillo, stands, is home to several table mountains, of which El Yunque is the most famous.
About the coffee, the rum, the cigars, the Sierra Maestra Mountains, the Bay of Pigs and the island of Isla de Pinos, about the Tropicana Cabaret, the sanctuary of the Cuban patroness Caridad del Cobre, about the Santeria, an African religion to which the descendants of slaves profess, about all this one could write many pages.
