A Difficult Memorabilia
After more than 60 years of confidential treatment, the Nazi archives of Bad Arolsen, which document the fates of 17.5 million victims of the Hitler regime, are now freely accessible.
The 47 million documents of the archive, which are housed in Bad Arolsen for a total length of 27 km, have not yet been read, unless with a humanitarian intention, i.e. individual and name-related, to consult a former victim or his/her relatives.
In May 2006, the eleven states, including Germany, France, Israel and the USA, which are responsible for their administration, agreed to make them accessible to researchers and historians.
After the ratification process of this decision has been completed, the opening has been valid since yesterday.
Hot information
Historians' access to Bad Arolsen will make it possible to conduct research, especially on the deportations of prisoners, the inmates of concentration camps and the state of health of forced labourers, explains Reto Meistern, head of these archives, which are administered by the International Committee of the Red Cross (CICR).
Until recently, several states, including Germany, were opposed to making these name-related documents available to the public due to the delicate nature of certain information.
Like, for example, the alleged homosexuality or mental disability of some deportation victims.
The prisoners' lists of the concentration camps or the arrest warrants issued by the Gestapo had been collected after the war for a practical reason: to find civilians who had been deported or subjected to forced labour, and possibly to provide them with evidence of their arrest in order to pave the way for their compensation.
Even today, more than 300 permanent employees in Bad Arolsen process tens of thousands of personal inquiries.
Nevertheless, part of the scientific community shows only a limited interest in access to Bad Arolsen.
One should not expect anything fundamentally new in these documents, explained Pr. Wolfgang Benz, head of the Research Center for Anti-Semitism of the Technical University of Berlin, 2006.
