New fears about gas dispute between Russia and Ukraine
A new price dispute is fading between Ukraine and Russia, which increases the risk of Russian exports being affected by fuel to Western Europe.
Most of Russia's natural gas exports to the European Union (EU) are channelled through Ukraine and every dispute between the two nations is closely monitored.
Kiev has warned that if Moscow increases the price it has to pay for natural gas, it will charge Russia for higher transit charges.
A previous conflict between the two states last year reduced deliveries to the EU states.
The recent dispute between Kiev and Moscow is happening at a time when the Ukrainian government and the Russian state gas monopoly Gazprom are trying to reach an agreement on how much Ukraine must pay for Russian gas in 2008.
According to Gazprom, Ukraine has to be charged more, as the Group has agreed to pay up to 50% additional for natural gas from neighbouring Turkmenistan.
Analysts say that this could mean Ukraine has to pay 40% more for Gazprom's imports.
"It is important for us to use our arguments as one of the most important gas transit states during talks," said Ukraine's Minister of Economic Affairs Anatoli Kinakh of the Reuters news agency.
"The changing gas prices should undoubtedly be linked to our arguments regarding the amount of transit fees [to Western Europe] via Ukraine."
In the last major gas dispute between Moscow and Kiev in January 2006, Gazprom cut deliveries to Ukraine.
This resulted in a fall in exports to Western Europe, which drastically increased prices.
Russian gas accounts for a quarter of the European Union's supply.
Russia has the world's largest gas deposits, but much of it remains underdeveloped.
As a result, Gazprom complements its own supplies with gas from Turkmenistan and other Central Asian former Soviet nations.
NHS "must control foreign workers"
The Scottish State Health Service must improve controls on criminal records for workers from outside Europe, said one member of the control body.
The recommendation of the main financial controller Robert Black came after a foreign doctor was brought to Scotland in connection with the attack on Glasgow airport in June.
Black also expressed concerns that the Scottish National Health Service did not have any precise ideas about the number of its foreign employees.
But his report pointed out that other important controls were carried out correctly in a sample of five health authorities.
The main financial controller investigated personnel recruited outside the countries of the European Economic Area as a result of the attack on Glasgow airport.
Bilal Abdullah, 28, an Iraqi doctor at the Royal Alexandra Hospital in Paisley, was arrested at the airport after an off-road vehicle was driven through the doors of the main airport terminal.
He was one of three doctors who appeared in a video broadcast at Old Bailey in October and was charged with the alleged car bomb attack in Britain.
The National Health Service is expected to carry out checks prior to the appointment of foreign staff to ensure that they have the necessary qualifications, experience and authorizations to work in the UK.
Although the health authorities use Disclosure Scotland to review criminal records, the Agency does not have the competence to obtain this information outside the UK.
The main examiner's report now states, among other recommendations, that the board should take up guidelines of the criminal record extract that help employers with controls in different countries.
"Although we have found evidence of these controls in some personnel records, they have not been carried out routinely," the report noted.
Black said the Scottish health authorities would follow their investigative guidelines to a large extent before hiring, but added: "Our report shows areas where the system can be improved to ensure that accurate information on the number of foreign health care workers is available."
BMA Scotland Chairman Dr. Peter Terry said it was "extremely unlikely" that investigations would identify people who could commit future terrorist attacks ahead of the deployment of potential NHS staff.
"The report states that current pre-employment tests of the NHS Scotland work well and it is not clear what added value the recommendations will deliver," he said.
The Scottish health authorities say that they currently have 1,161 foreign employees, the vast majority of whom are doctors and nurses.
However, the financial controller warned that the number was probably higher, also because the board members had problems identifying those employees who were on leave indefinitely.
The investigation also found that established control procedures were largely complied with by NHS authorities in Ayrshire, Arran, Grampian, Greater Glasgow and Clyde, Lanarkshire, and Lothian.
These include passport, work permit and qualification checks.
the Scottish Government is currently reviewing its policy and guidelines for pre-employment controls for foreign staff in the NHS.
Nicola Sturgeon, Secretary of Health, said: "It was my concern to do this work in the face of the terrorist attack at Glasgow Airport."
It added that the Scottish Government, in conjunction with the health authorities, would take into account the report's recommendations and ensure that best practices would be reflected in updated guidance on control investigations prior to the appointment of all staff, including those from abroad, whose publication is scheduled for next month.
