Billions of years ago, Venus would have dominated conditions that would have been very similar to those on earth and could even have been habitable, scientists today believe.
But because of the unchecked carbon dioxide greenhouse effect, the erosion of the atmosphere by solar radiation and a slower rotational pace, Venus took a completely different course of development.
Today, the planet is deprived of water and has a surface temperature that is hot enough to melt lead and is devastated by hurricane-strong winds and lightning storms.
The findings of the space probe Venus Express of the European Space Agency, which has examined the planet for a year, provide a sobering view of how the Earth could develop in the face of catastrophic climate changes.
