Venus is the hellish twin of the earth
Despite its hostile atmosphere, Venus is more similar than previously thought: The European space probe "Venus Express" has discovered lightning in the atmosphere and wind vortexes at the poles, as they occur on Earth in winter.
For almost three decades, scientists have been suggesting that it flashes on Venus.
Now the European probe "Venus Express" has provided proof - it detects electromagnetic waves at the edge of the atmosphere: The lightnings on Venus shoot at an altitude of about 56 kilometres from cloud to cloud, reports Christopher Russel from the University of California in Los Angeles in the science magazine "Nature".
According to the famous "prime soup theory", lightning has caused life on Earth to develop: thunderstorms have stimulated reactions in the ocean that have led to the formation of amino acids, the building blocks of life.
Not so on Venus: "If there ever was life there, it must have been in very early history," explains Sean Solomon of the Carnegie Institution in Washington.
Today there is hardly anything living on the surface of Venus: the atmosphere is about a hundred times denser than on Earth, with temperatures of 500 degrees Celsius.
" Venus may be the devil's will on Earth, but it's a twin," Russel said.
Why Venus, which is so similar to Earth in mass and size, has taken such a completely different development, is the fundamental question of the Esa mission.
The launch of "Venus Express" in November 2005 was a milestone for Venus research, as since the beginning of the nineties no longer a probe was on its way specifically for the exploration of this planet.
According to the researchers, the latest research results, which are now presented in several "nature" articles, not only underline the uniqueness of Venus within the solar system.
"They also show that the similarities of our neighboring planet with Earth are greater than initially assumed," the Esa informs.
In addition to the already known whirlwind at the North Pole, the researchers also found a cloud strudel at the South Pole, which rotates much faster.
The phenomenon is reminiscent of air flows in the terrestrial winter hemisphere, writes a team of researchers led by Giuseppe Piccioni of the Italian Istituto di Astrofisica Spaziale e Fisica Cosmica.
The second-tinnerest planet of the solar system has almost the same mass as the Earth and is almost as large with a diameter of 12,100 kilometers.
The planet, also known as the morning or evening star, orbits the Sun in just under 225 days.
But it revolves much slower around itself: a Venus Day lasts 243 Earth days.
Although Venus with surface temperatures of 460 degrees Celsius and a pressure of 92 bar hardly resembles the Earth, scientists assume that both planets have emerged under very similar conditions.
Both gathered water that remained on Earth in oceans, but on which Venus was lost in space.
And while carbon dioxide is fixed on Earth in carbonate rocks, it makes up most of the atmosphere on Venus.
