Whoever connects the terms Sweden and wooden box thinks of Ikea, but not Andy Warhol.
Or is it?
Currently, fabricated wooden boxes cast dark shadows on Warhol's catalogue of works in Sweden.
Most of the ninety-four Brillo boxes listed there are forgeries of the Stockholm type.
After the Swedish newspaper "Expressen" raised doubts about the authenticity of Andy Warhol's Brillo Boxes of 1968 a few months ago, internal research at the Moderna Museet in Stockholm now leads to a sobering result: The six "Brillo Boxes", which the former museum director Pontus Hultén donated to the Moderna Museet in 1995, are copies - and probably also the majority of the approximately one hundred other Brillo Boxes of the "Skip Stockholm" type, which are in circulation on the international art market.
The prehistory is intertwined, a confusing concatenation of artistic and curatorial productions.
In 1964 Warhol created his first "Brillo Boxes" in New York, painted wooden boxes based on the red-blue-white design of the cardboard boxes of the "Brillo" soap powder.
An exhibition of his works at the Moderna Museet in 1968, with Warhol's consent, exhibited hundreds of Brillo boxes made of cardboard: these did not come from Warhol (for cost reasons), but were delivered directly from the Brillo carton factory.
These were not works of art, but their models, mere exhibits.
At the same time, Warhol probably granted permission in 1968 to produce a few Brillo wooden crates in Sweden, which were not exhibited in the Moderna Museet.
Contemporary witnesses now speak of about fifteen boxes, which at that time were rightly included in the art and auction history as authorized original Andy Warhol Brillo boxes with the designation "Style Stockholm".
Some of them have earned more than $100,000 at auctions.
The problem now is that the legendary museum director Pontus Hultén later falsely claimed that around a hundred wooden crates were produced and exhibited in Sweden in 1968, which Warhol then left to him.
In fact, Hultén's 105 boxes were not produced until 1990 in Malmö for an exhibition in St. Petersburg.
Warhol was dead three years ago.
Lars Byström, chief conservator at the Moderna Museet, has examined the six museum's own Brillo boxes, three of which were made in Stockholm in 1968: their press plates were first primed and sanded, then white oil paint was applied with a brush.
The structure of the 1990 copies, on the other hand, reveals that the paint was applied directly to the press chipboard with a paint roll without a primer - moreover, it is not oil but acrylic paint.
"These boxes were not authorized by the artist and should be removed from the official list of Andy Warhol's Brillo boxes," says Lars Nittve, director of the Moderna Museet: "If the 'Andy Warhol Art Authentication Board' in New York does not come to a different conclusion, the Moderna Museet will classify the six boxes in its collection as copies/exhibitions."
Already in July, the Authentication Board announced that it would investigate the "serious accusations" raised in the case of soap powder boxes.
Since then, however, they have been shrouded in relentless silence.
